observations.recommendation:
We recommended Management to (a) prepare the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund Investment Plan (LDRRMFIP) annually to present the specific projects and activities to be funded out of the 70% allocation for disaster mitigation, prevention and preparedness; (b) require the LDRRMO, through the LDRRMC and Local Development Council (LDC), to prepare the Report on Sources and Utilization of DRRMF to be certified correct by the Local Accountant and submitted to the COA Auditor of the LGU on or before the 15th day after the end of each month; (c) utilize the LDRRMF in accordance with the guidelines; (d) submit to the audit team, as additional supporting document to the disbursement on food supplies, the distribution of each food item to each of the recipients; 

(e) transfer the unexpended balance to the Special Trust Fund and disclose the details of the unexpended balance of the DRRMF in the Notes to Financial Statements to provide adequate information to stakeholders about the Fund; and
(f) subject all procurements to public bidding unless the conditions are met for the use of alternative mode of procurement.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive
(a) create a new Municipal Solid Waste Management Board comprised of officials who could actively perform their respective duties and functions as intended;
(b) cause the completion of the 10-year Solid Waste Management Plan (SWMP); (c) address the issue on the controlled open dumpsites and include in the SWMP provisions for their closure or eventual phase out in accordance with the guidelines set by the Ecological Solid Waste Management Act of 2000;
(d) through the Liga ng mga Barangay, encourage active participation of barangay officials to support the solid waste management program of the government by educating their respective constituents on the proper segregation of reusable or recyclable materials from compostable wastes;
(e) comply with the requirements of the law on waste segregation by placing trash bins with proper labels on key areas of the Municipality and by collecting only those garbage that are properly segregated;


(f) provide necessary support in enjoining the 8 barangays to establish their own MRF;
(g) recommend to the Sangguniang Bayan policies and possible measures that will ensure full compliance by the barangays on the provisions of R.A. No. 9003; and (h) fully implement the Municipal Environment Code and No Littering Ordinance.

We recommended that Management (a) refrain from accommodating expenditures on activities for which the DepEd has the direct mandate to execute;



(b) request the Local School Board to prepare a balanced budget with conscious and concerted efforts of observing compliance with the legal and regulatory requirements on SEF budgeting, allocation and utilization; and
(c) submit documents to support the attendance of teaching and non teaching to trainings and seminar to the Audit Team for our evaluation.

We recommended that Management (a) promulgate policies on the issuance of mobile phone units;

(b) stop the practice of splitting purchase requisitions or contracts and other related transactions pursuant to COA Circular No. 76-41 to promote effective competition and transparency in the procurement process and obtain a fair and equitable contract for the best interest of the government;
(c) request the refund of withholding tax shouldered by the municipality from the person responsible; and
(d) observe the limitations in the issuance of mobile phones to entitled officials, which should not be in excess of one unit per official.

We  reiterated our previous years’ recommendation  that  management (a) direct the Municipal Accountant to coordinate with the Municipal Assessor and Treasurer in establishing the accurate amount of basic RPT and SET receivable from each taxpayer as of  the end of 2015;



(b) require the Accounting Office to set up and maintain updated index card for each taxpayer to facilitate the establishment of the accurate amount of collectible from each taxpayer;
(c) pass the journal entry voucher to adjust the amount of recorded receivables to reconcile the general ledger balance with the amount actually collectible from each taxpayer based on the certified list of collectibles and reflected in the taxpayer’s ledger; and (d) direct the  Municipal  Treasurer  to invariably furnish  the  Municipal  Accountant  a  duly  certified  list showing  the  names  of  the  taxpayers  and  the  actual  due  and  collectible  for  the  year  as basis in  setting  up  the Real Property Tax  and  Special Education Tax  receivables due for the year.

We reiterated our previous years’ recommendations and  management agreed to   (a) form an inventory committee that will conduct an annual count of all  PPE items including the preparation and submission of the inventory report/RPCPPE;



(b) exert more efforts in tracing/retrieving accounting records that will support the prior year balance of ₱1,745,760.29 from the Trust Fund; (c) require the Accountant to transfer  the PPE  recorded  in  the  Trust  Fund  in  the books  of  the  General  Fund;
(d) perform constant follow up with the offices concerned to facilitate the immediate registration and titling of the several  lots in the name of the municipality; and


(e) direct the Municipal Accountant to perform a reconciliation of the discrepancies between the balances per FS and Lapsing schedule.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive  (a)  require the Accountant and the Treasurer to stop the payment of annual dues to various organizations and associations not in conformity with R.A. No. 7160 for lack of legal basis; 



(b) require the Municipal Budget Officer to refrain from obligating claims without the available appropriations for the purpose; otherwise, require the Sangguniang Bayan to issue resolution for the realignment/issuance of supplemental of budget;   (c) advise the Municipal Accountant to see to it that claims for the membership, dues, and contributions be substantiated with the necessary budget and approved plans and programs as basis for the amount to be paid; and 


(d) advise the Municipal Treasurer that payments for the purpose made to duly recognized leagues and federations under the law be acknowledged with the prescribed government Accountable Form No. 51 or official receipts duly registered with the Bureau of Internal Revenue.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive(a) require the MDRRMC to submit to the Audit Team documentation to support the distribution and disposition of  the stock piled goods purchased in 2014; (b) be circumspect in the stockpiling of perishable goods to avoid spoilage thereof considering that the Municipality is not generally exposed to high risk of flooding while supermarkets are highly accessible from the municipality;
(c) instruct the BAC and the procuring officials to purchase rice and grocery goods from only authorized or legitimate dealer/wholesalers to obtain the most advantageous prices;
(d) instruct the BAC to be diligent in obtaining reasonable agency budget estimates thru proper canvasses; and (e) prioritize the use of the LDRRMF to solve  the problem of constricted and silted rivers/creeks and inadequate drainage to minimize flooding.

We recommended and the management agreed to (a) direct the BAC Committee members to diligently perform their duties in evaluating eligibilities of suppliers; (b) procure only from bonafide/authorized dealers/resellers to obtain the  lowest and reasonable price and warranty services;
(c) desist from entering into contracts from middleman in renting back hoe and dump trucks;
(d) submit justifications and lacking requirements for the questioned transactions with Ricothel Trading, for the evaluation of the Audit Team; and (e) direct the Treasurer to collect the underpayment of business tax from the subject supplier.
